Caffeine is one of the most widely consumed psychoactive substances on the planet. Prior individual-level research has found links between caffeine intake and depression and mortality, but almost all of that work is within a single country. We wanted to ask a different question: do these patterns appear across countries? And if they do, can we separate caffeine from the obvious confounders like wealth, smoking, and alcohol?
Our primary question is: across countries, is higher estimated caffeine consumption per capita associated with lower depression burden or lower all-cause mortality? Our secondary questions ask whether the dominant caffeine source matters, specifically coffee versus tea, and whether any association survives controlling for GDP and lifestyle factors.
This is an inference project, not a prediction one. We're not building a model to classify countries. We're testing whether a relationship exists and how robust it is.

